128 11. A student may be promoted to grade four despite scoring "at risk" on the
129 reading screener if the student has a good cause exemption. Good cause exemptions
130 shall be limited to the following:
131 (1) Students with disabilities who have an approved individualized education
132 plan developed under the federal Individuals with Disabilities Education Act (IDEA), 20
133 U.S.C. Section 1401 et seq., as amended, that indicates that participation in the
134 statewide assessment program is not appropriate, consistent with state and federal law;

HCS HB 2872 9
135 (2) Students with disabilities who participate in the statewide summative English
136 language arts assessment and who have either of the following plans reflecting that the
137 student has received intensive reading intervention for more than two years but still
138 demonstrates a substantial reading deficiency:
139 (a) An approved individualized education plan developed under the federal
140 Individuals with Disabilities Education Act (IDEA), 20 U.S.C. Section 1401 et seq., as
141 amended; or
142 (b) A 504 plan created under Section 504 of the federal Rehabilitation Act of
143 1973, 29 U.S.C. Section 794, as amended;
144 (3) Students identified as English language learners who have had fewer than
145 two years of instruction in an English language learner program; and
146 (4) Students who have already been retained at least once in any of grades
147 kindergarten through grade three.
148 12. Requests for a good cause exemption shall be made in accordance with the
149 following requirements:
150 (1) Documentation shall be submitted from the student's teacher to the school
151 principal indicating that the promotion of the student is appropriate. Such
152 documentation shall consist only of the good cause exemption being requested and
153 the existing reading improvement plan or individualized education plan, as applicable;
154 and
155 (2) The school principal shall review and discuss the recommendation with the
156 teacher and parent or guardian and make the determination as to whether the student
157 qualifies for one of the good cause exemptions described in subsection 10 in this section.
158 If the school principal determines that the student is eligible for one of the good cause
159 exemptions based on the documentation provided, the school principal shall make such
160 recommendation in writing to the superintendent of the school district. The
161 superintendent shall accept or reject the school principal's recommendation in writing.
162 13. (1) The school district shall assist schools with providing written notification
163 to the parent of any student who is retained that:
164 (a) Such student has not met the reading level required for promotion;
165 (b) The reasons the student is not eligible for a good cause exemption; and
166 (c) That such student will be retained in grade three.
167 (2) The notification required under subdivision (1) of this subsection shall
168 include a description of the proposed interventions and supports that will be provided to
169 the child to remedy the identified area or areas of reading deficiency in the following
170 school year.
171 [5.] 14. Each school district or charter school shall do all of the following:

HCS HB 2872 10
172 (1) Provide students who are identified as having a reading deficiency or substantial
173 readingdeficiency [in reading] under [subsection 1] subsections 5 and 6of this section, have
